ce":"Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, Frankrijk","Abreschviller, France":"Abreschviller, Moselle, Lorraine, Frankrijk","Abreschviller, Moselle, Lorraine, France":"Abreschviller, Moselle, Lorraine, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1590–1663":"1590–about1663","1593–1660":"1593–1660","1619–1682":"1619–1682","1630–1660":"about1630–1660","1630–Male":"about1630–Deceased","1630–1675":"about1630–1675","1555–1637":"1555–about1637","–1637":"–about1637","before 1630":"before 1630","1660":"1660","1682":"1682","1593":"1593","1590":"1590","1610":"1610","1555":"1555","1598":"1598","1675":"1675","1630":"about 1630","1663":"about 1663","environ 1619":"about 1619","1619":"1619","1618":"1618","1637":"about 1637","1648":"1648","Urmatt, France":"Urmatt, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France","Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, France":"Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France","Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France":"Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France","Abreschviller, France":"Abreschviller, Moselle, Lorraine, France","Abreschviller, Moselle, Lorraine, France":"Abreschviller, Moselle, Lorraine, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marchal","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gilles, Jacques, Maryse, Philippe, Pierre, Veronique.","French and Walloon: status name or occupational name from Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i> ‘marshal’. The term is of ancient Germanic origin (from <i>marah</i> ‘horse, mare’ + <i>scalc</i> ‘servant’) and was originally applied to a man who looked after horses. In the Middle Ages it also came to be used on the one hand as an occupational name for a farrier, and on the other as a status name for an officer of state, in particular a member of a royal household with military responsibilities. Compare English   Marshall   and 2 below.","English: variant of   Marshall  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland, and is found mainly in Glamorgan, Wales."],"variants":[{"name":"Marshall","meanings":["English: usually an occupational name ‘farrier’, occasionally a status name ‘chief official of a royal household or court; a high officer of state’, from Middle English <i>mareshal</i> and Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i>. An even wider range of meanings is found in some other languages: compare for example Polish <b>Marszałek</b> (see   Marszalek  ). This name has been established in Ireland since the 13th century. It is also borne by Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","Americanized form of German   Marschall  .","Americanized form of French   Mercier  ."]},{"name":"Marichal","meanings":["French (northern), Walloon, and Spanish (Canary Islands): variant of French   Marchal  . This surname, which is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium, is established in the Canary Island since the 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Humbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. However, it was not common in Britain in the Middle Ages, and has always had a Continental flavour. It was used by Vladimir Nabokov for the name of the demented pederast,  Humbert Humbert , who is the narrator in his novel Lolita (  1955 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1670184,"age":8,"year":"1598","julianDay":2304718,"title":"Edict of Nantes ","description":"Under the rule of Henry IV of France the Edict of Nantes was issued giving the people some religious liberty. The edict brought an end to the religious wars that were going on at the time. ","url":"https://www.britannica.com/event/Edict-of-Nantes","urlTitle":"Encyclopedia Britannica- Edict of Nantes","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1355839,"age":20,"year":"1610","julianDay":2309101,"description":"Reigns of Louis X